## Goal

Create application layer for spatial query orchestration. This is MEDIUM RISK - we're adding new service layer alongside existing code.

## Estimated Effort

4-6 hours

## What to Build

Create service layer in `public/js/spatial/application/`:

### 1. spatial-service.js - Main Service

**Purpose:** Orchestrate spatial query lifecycle (validate → compile → execute → update state)

**Key Features:**
- SpatialQueryService class
- Handles concurrency ("latest result wins" with cancellation)
- Caches compiled queries (performance optimization)
- Manages execution state transitions
- Emits events for side effects (NOT core logic)
- Explicit error handling

**Concurrency Handling:**
```javascript
async executeQuery(query) {
  // Cancel previous if still running
  if (this.currentExecution) {
    this.currentExecution.abort();
  }

  const controller = new AbortController();
  this.currentExecution = controller;

  // Execute with cancellation checks
  // Update state only if not cancelled
}
```

### 2. executor.js - Execution Helper

Orchestrates: Build SQL → Execute query → Handle cancellation → Return metadata

### 3. event-bus.js - Event Emitter

Lightweight event bus for service layer (isolated from global state)

## Wiring into app.js

**Feature Flag Pattern:**
```javascript
const useNewArchitecture = state.config?.features?.spatial_new_architecture || false;

if (useNewArchitecture) {
  const spatialService = new SpatialQueryService({ state, eventBus, db });
  // Wire event listeners
} else {
  // Keep existing code
}
```

## Testing Strategy

Unit tests with mocks + Integration tests with real modules

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] event-bus.js, executor.js, spatial-service.js created
- [ ] Service handles concurrency (cancellation works)
- [ ] Service caches compiled queries
- [ ] Events emitted for side effects
- [ ] Feature flag in config.json
- [ ] Both architectures produce same results
- [ ] All tests passing

